	  <h1 class="siteTitle">Phase Oscillators (under construction)</h1>

	  We can observe many rhythmic systems in nature.
	  Such systems are described by dynamical systems mathematically, although most of them have often too many degrees of freedom.
	  The phase reduction technique [1] reduces a limit-cycle system even with external forces to a phase oscillator system with only one phase variable, which helps our mathematical and numerical analysis. 
	  <br>
	  Coupled limit-cycle system is reduced coupled phase oscillator system by the phase reduction, and as a representative model the Kuramoto model has been extensively studied.
	  <br>
	  weak coupling &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&larr; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &rarr;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; strong coupling
	  <br>
	  <IMG src="test_K_0.0.gif" width="240" height="200"><IMG src="test_K_0.5.gif" width="240" height="200"><IMG src="test_K_1.0.gif" width="240" height="200"><IMG src="test_K_5.0.gif" width="240" height="200">
	  <br>
	  In the Kuramoto model, the oscillators evolve according to the equations:
	  <br>
	  <IMG src="latex-image-1.png" width="30%" height="30%">
	  <br>
	  The oscillators have the natural frequencies, which are in some cases assumed to obey the Lorentz distribution:
	  <br>
	  <IMG src="lorentz.png" width="20%" height="20%">
	  <br>
	  The above figures show that the system undergoes the synchronization trainsition when the coupling strength K is increased.
	  That is, with small K the oscillators move incoherently while with strong coupling they cooperate and tend to have similar phases.

